  "frozen": true,
  "context_summary": "3-year-old boy brought in by his mother for ear tugging and fussiness over the past two days, on top of nasal congestion and a runny nose that started about five days ago. He has not had a fever checked at home until this morning. Otoscopy has not yet been performed. The doctor is about to decide whether this looks like a straightforward viral URI with eustachian tube congestion or an evolving acute otitis media that needs to be confirmed on exam.",
  "good_next_question": "Did the fever start before the ear tugging began, or did the fever show up around the same time as, or after, the ear pain started?",
  "rationale": "AOM classically develops as a bacterial superinfection layered on top of a preceding viral URI, so the temporal relationship between a new fever and the onset of ear symptoms is a useful discriminator before otoscopy even happens. A fever that appears simultaneously with or after the acute onset of ear tugging suggests a new, localized process in the middle ear rather than just the ongoing viral illness, raising suspicion for AOM and prompting a careful look for a bulging, erythematous tympanic membrane. If the fever has been present all along as part of the cold, with ear tugging just now emerging without any new temperature spike, simple eustachian tube dysfunction from the URI is more likely and doesn't necessarily need antibiotics. This question is prioritized over asking about pain severity alone, since young children can't reliably grade pain, but a caregiver can usually reconstruct a rough timeline of fever versus ear symptom onset.",
  "tags": [
    "ent",
    "acute_otitis_media",
    "aom",
    "pediatric",
    "peds",
    "fever"
  ],
